    "content": "1st: B — 2nd: A — 3rd: C — Reason: The collection's most Wittgensteinian quality is that the essays ARE the philosophy -- they function as philosophical experiments on the reader (see my Analysis Report, S2). A translator's preface is essential to alert English readers that experiential sequences are load-bearing, not merely illustrative, and to explain the transliteration of \"Jing\" and the -scape system. Without this apparatus, Western readers will read these essays as standard analytic arguments and miss the performative dimension entirely. But the author's own voice should come first (preface by the author), because the collection's authority rests on the author's independent philosophical achievement -- the translator should frame, not front. Option C (translator only, no author) would erase the author's voice from the paratext, which contradicts the collection's insistence that meaning originates from the individual subject. Option A (author only) would work if the author's preface happened to address English-specific reading challenges, but it likely won't -- the terminological bridge (Jing, the poetic, constancy, the non-rational, etc.) needs explicit translator mediation."
